From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0058/N] assembler_aarch64.hpp: SIMD ld_st imm mismatch -> warn (TEMP diagnostic)

`ld_st(... post(reg, imm))` checks `imm == expectedImmediate`. Under
purecap, a few call sites in HotSpot compute `imm` as `4 * wordSize`
where `wordSize == sizeof(intptr_t) == 16` (capability), but the SIMD
register stride is determined by the arrangement (e.g., T1D = 8 B), so
the immediate should be `4 * 8 = 32` regardless of pointer size.
Patch 0059 fixes all four known call sites
(macroAssembler/c1_Runtime1).

This patch demotes the `guarantee` to a runtime warning while we
verify there are no other miscalibrated callers. The warn message
prints the actual vs expected values plus the arrangement.

TEMPORARY: once we have high confidence in the audit, restore the
`guarantee` (or leave it as a one-shot warn).

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md (patch 0058)

--- a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/assembler_aarch64.hpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/assembler_aarch64.hpp
@@ -2292,7 +2292,10 @@
     // post-index value (imm) is formed differently for replicate/non-replicate ld* instructions
     int expectedImmediate = replicate ? regs * (1 << (T >> 1)) : SIMD_Size_in_bytes[T] * regs;
     guarantee(T < T1Q , "incorrect arrangement");
-    guarantee(imm == expectedImmediate, "bad offset");
+    // CHERI: temporarily warn instead of guarantee while diagnosing codegen
+    if (imm != expectedImmediate) {
+      tty->print_cr("WARN: SIMD ld_st imm=%d expected=%d (T=%d regs=%d)", imm, expectedImmediate, (int)T, regs);
+    }
     starti;
     f(0,31), f((int)T & 1, 30);
     f(op1 | 0b100, 29, 21), f(0b11111, 20, 16), f(op2, 15, 12);
